SIMPLE: fight
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fight
<hw>Fight</hw> <pr>(f⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fought</conjf> <pr>(f⟦add⟧t)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Fighting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fihten</ets>, <ets>fehten</ets>, AS. <ets>feohtan</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>vechten</ets>, OHG. <ets>fehtan</ets>, G. <ets>fechten</ets>, Sw.
<ets>f⟦aum⟧kta</ets>, Dan. <ets>fegte</ets>, and perh. to E.
<ets>fist</ets>; cf. L. <ets>pugnare</ets> to fight, <ets>pugnus</ets>
fist.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strive or contened for victory, with
armies or in single combat; to attempt to defeat, subdue, or destroy an
enemy, either by blows or weapons; to contend in arms; -- followed by
<xex>with</xex> or <xex>against</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You do <qex>fight</qex> against your country's foes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>fight</qex> with thee no man of arms will deign.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act in opposition to anything; to struggle
against; to contend; to strive; to make resistance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fight shy</b></col>, <cd>to avoid meeting fairly or at
close quarters; to keep out of reach.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fight
<hw>Fight</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To carry on, or wage,
as a conflict, or battle; to win or gain by struggle, as one's way; to
sustain by fighting, as a cause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had to <qex>fight</qex> his way through the world.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>fought</qex> a good fight.</q> <rj><qau>2 Tim. iv.
7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To contend with in battle; to war against; <as>as,
they <ex>fought</ex> the enemy in two pitched battles; the sloop
<ex>fought</ex> the frigate for three hours.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to fight; to manage or maneuver in a fight;
<as>as, to <ex>fight</ex> cocks; to <ex>fight</ex> one's
ship.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fight it out</b></col>, <cd>to fight until a decisive
and conclusive result is reached.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 558 --></p>

<p><ent>Fight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fight
<hw>Fight</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fight</ets>,
<ets>feht</ets>, AS. <ets>feoht</ets>. See <er>Fight</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A battle; an engagement; a contest in
arms; a combat; a violent conflict or struggle for victory, between
individuals or between armies, ships, or navies, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who now defies thee thrice to single <qex>fight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A struggle or contest of any kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Strength or disposition for fighting; pugnacity;
<as>as, he has a great deal of <ex>fight</ex> in him</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A screen for the combatants in ships.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Up with your <qex>fights</qex>, and your nettings prepare.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Running fight</b></col>, <cd>a fight in which the enemy
is continually chased; also, one which continues without definite end or
result.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Combat; engagement; contest; struggle; encounter;
fray; affray; action; conflict. See <er>Battle</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fighter</ent>⟦br⟧
